Comment: The Saragossa can be quite dangerous as a transposition opening. For instance it is plausible that after d5 or d5 White could play c4 and transpose to a symmetrical English or Benoni respectively with colours reversed. Similarly after e5 a Sicilian is reached, this is why I like to play Nf6 and retain flexibility
Going into a more mainstream opening
Going into a more mainstream opening
c5 is an alternative but in this line it's not actually that easy to prove compensation for the pawn after dxc5 and the pawn can't be quickly picked back up

Bd6 was fully viable but I wanted to see how White intended to deal with the attack on the b pawn. There aren't any tactical resources to give the pawn away thankfully. There are often tricks with Na3 and Nb5 exploiting wk dark squares in d4, d5 openings but the fianchetto of the light squared bishop kills these off
